Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** that you can drop into an OCaml project and compile with a single `ocamlc/ocamlopt` (or `dune`) command.  
It follows the “single mutable custom block” pattern, which is the usual way to get a *hot* per‑iteration callback without allocating a new OCaml value for every frame.

* **`pcapng.mli`** – the public OCaml interface.  
* **`pcapng_stubs.c`** – the C‑/C++‑side implementation (compiled as C++).  

Both files are written so that they can be compiled together with the libpcapng C++ library (the exact libpcapng API is only sketched – replace the placeholders with the real calls from the library you are using).

---

## 1. `pcapng.mli` – public OCaml API

```ocaml
(* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   OCaml bindings for libpcapng – iterator over frames
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(** Opaque handle for an opened pcapng file. *)
type t

(** Opaque handle that represents a *single* frame.  The same OCaml value
    is re‑used for every iteration step – only its internal fields are
    overwritten by the C stub.  This makes the per‑frame cost essentially
    the cost of the OCaml callback itself. *)
type frame

(** Open a pcapng file.  Raises [Failure] if the file cannot be opened. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Close the file and free all native resources.  After calling this,
    the handle must not be used again. *)
val close : t -> unit

(** Iterate over **all** frames in the file, invoking the supplied OCaml
    function for each frame.  The callback receives a single argument of
    type [frame].  The callback must **not** raise; any exception aborts
    the iteration and propagates to the caller. *)
val iter : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** Accessors for the data that lives inside a [frame] value.
    All of them are O(1); the only allocation is performed by
    [frame_data] which copies the raw bytes into a fresh [Bytes.t].
    If you need a zero‑copy view you can add a Bigarray accessor
    in the same style. *)

(** Return a copy of the raw packet bytes. *)
val frame_data : frame -> Bytes.t

(** Length of the packet (in bytes). *)
val frame_len : frame -> int

(** Timestamp of the packet, expressed as seconds since the epoch
    (the same representation that libpcapng uses). *)
val frame_timestamp : frame -> float
```

