## 3. How to compile

Assuming the files are placed in a directory `src/` and the libpcapng library is available as `-lpcapng` (replace with the real name), a simple `ocamlc`/`ocamlopt` command looks like:

```sh
# OCaml side (produces pcapng.cmi and pcapng.cmo / .cmx)
ocamlc -c src/pcapng.mli
ocamlopt -c src/pcapng.mli   # or ocamlc -c for bytecode

# C++ stub (produces a .o that can be linked)
g++ -std=c++17 -I$(ocamlc -where) -fPIC -c src/pcapng_stubs.c -o src/pcapng_stubs.o

# Link everything together (bytecode or native)
ocamlc -custom -o my_program \
        src/pcapng.cmo src/pcapng_stubs.o -lpcapng -lstdc++

# or, for native code:
ocamlopt -o my_program \
         src/pcapng.cmx src/pcapng_stubs.o -lpcapng -lstdc++
```

If you are using **Dune**, the stanza is even simpler:

```dune
(executable
 (name my_program)
 (modules pcapng main)          ; `main.ml` is your user code
 (foreign_stubs
  (language c)                 ; Dune will compile it as C++ because of .cxx
  (names pcapng_stubs)
  (flags (:standard -std=c++17))
  (libraries pcapng)))         ; link with libpcapng
```

Replace `pcapng::Reader`, `pcapng::Iterator`, and `pcapng::Packet` with the exact types provided by the version of libpcapng you are using. The skeleton above already shows where to plug those calls in.

